Subject: [PATCH v2] Fix memory corruption in file system driver
Date: Thu, 07 Apr 2005 12:00:00 +0000
Message-Id: <nice005.test@kernel.example.org>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

From: Jane Developer <jane@example.org>

This patch fixes a memory corruption bug in the file system driver that
was introduced in commit 7e8f9a0b. The issue occurs when the driver
attempts to read beyond the allocated buffer during directory traversal.

The fix ensures that all buffer boundary checks are performed before any
data is accessed. This was found during a routine code review and
confirmed by stress testing the driver under concurrent workloads.

Additionally, this patch cleans up several related error paths that
failed to properly release allocated memory on failure, which could
lead to memory leaks under certain conditions.

Changes since v1:
 - Addressed review comments from the maintainer
 - Added boundary check for the edge case reported by the test team
 - Improved error handling in the cleanup path

Signed-off-by: Jane Developer <jane@example.org>
Reviewed-by: Senior Engineer <senior@example.org>

---
 drivers/fs/example/driver.c | 24 ++++++++++++++++--------
 1 file changed, 16 insertions(+), 8 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/fs/example/driver.c b/drivers/fs/example/driver.c
index abc1234..def5678 100644
--- a/drivers/fs/example/driver.c
+++ b/drivers/fs/example/driver.c
@@ -142,6 +142,7 @@ static int driver_read(struct inode *inode, struct file *file)
 err_alloc:
+       kfree(buffer);
        release_lock(inode);
        return -ENOMEM;
